In .NET MAUI, use `Application.Current.RequestedTheme` and the `RequestedThemeChanged` event. To override, set `Application.Current.UserAppTheme`.

```csharp
// Detect current theme
AppTheme currentTheme = Application.Current.RequestedTheme;
// Returns AppTheme.Light, AppTheme.Dark, or AppTheme.Unspecified

// Subscribe to real-time changes
Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    AppTheme newTheme = e.RequestedTheme;
    Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to: {newTheme}");
    // Update UI or re-apply styles here
};

// Force a specific theme (overrides system setting)
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Revert to following the system setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

**Key points:**

| Property / Event | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `RequestedTheme` | Read the current system theme |
| `RequestedThemeChanged` | Fires when the OS theme toggles |
| `UserAppTheme` | Set to force a theme; set to `Unspecified` to follow the system |

**XAML-side**, you can use `AppThemeBinding` to react declaratively:

```xml
<Label Text="Hello"
       TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=Black, Dark=White}" />
```

**Typical pattern in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        RequestedThemeChanged += OnThemeChanged;
    }

    void OnThemeChanged(object sender, AppThemeChangedEventArgs e)
    {
        Debug.WriteLine($"System theme is now: {e.RequestedTheme}");
        // e.g. swap a ResourceDictionary, update a viewmodel flag, etc.
    }
}
```

Setting `UserAppTheme` to `Dark` or `Light` suppresses `RequestedThemeChanged` from firing (the app is no longer following the system). Setting it back to `Unspecified` re-enables system tracking.
